<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="271" pageId="3" pageNumber="270" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1122,2011]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="271" pageId="3" pageNumber="270">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1950,1975]" pageId="3" pageNumber="270">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haran" authorityYear="2018" box="[349,584,1950,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adjamati">
<emphasis box="[349,584,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="270">Smicronyx adjamati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffmann" authorityYear="1954" box="[798,971,1950,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remaudierei">
<emphasis box="[798,971,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="270">S. remaudierei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (see discussion on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffmann" authorityYear="1954" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remaudierei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="270">S. remaudierei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Within this species group, it can be distinguished from 
<emphasis box="[971,1351,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="270">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffmann" authorityYear="1954" box="[971,1139,1986,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="remaudierei">S. remaudierei</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoffmann" authorityYear="1968" box="[1203,1351,1986,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bisignatus">S. bisignatus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
by the absence of a distinct ventral tooth on the femora, and from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haran" authorityYear="2018" box="[843,1014,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassithorax">
<emphasis box="[843,1014,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">S. crassithorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its narrower prothorax. It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haran" authorityYear="2018" box="[380,534,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zambianus">
<emphasis box="[380,534,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">S. zambianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its reddish integuments and its elongate elytra of w/l ratio: 0.64 (black integuments and w/l ratio: 
<quantity box="[452,531,223,248]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7779999999999998" pageId="4" pageNumber="271" unit="in" value="0.7">0.70 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haran" authorityYear="2018" box="[538,686,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zambianus">
<emphasis box="[538,686,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">S. zambianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haran" authorityYear="2018" box="[709,934,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Smicronyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="adjamati">
<emphasis box="[709,934,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">Smicronyx adjamati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species of the species group with the apex of the penis acuminate in the apical half (
<figureCitation box="[714,803,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[196,1389,189,1792]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[165,1416,189,1815]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Penis of Smicronyx from tropical Africa, in dorsal (left) and lateral (right) view. A. Smicronyx bisignatus Hoffmann, holotype ♂. B. S. remaudierei Hoffmann, holotype ♂. C. S. adjamati, sp. n., holotype ♂. D. S. crassithorax sp. n., paratype ♀. E. S. zambianus sp. n. holotype ♂. F. S. syriacus Faust, specimen from Israel (♂). G. S. gossypii Marshall, holotype ♂. H. S. albosquamosus Wollaston, specimen from Israel (♂). I. S. pauperculus Wollaston, specimen from Tanzania (♂). J. S. rufus sp. n., holotype ♂. K. S. zonatus sp. n., holotype ♂. L. S. kenyanus sp. n., holotype ♂. M. S. namibicus sp. n., holotype ♂. N. S. kiboanus Voss, paratype ♂. O. S. guineanus Voss, specimen from Senegal (♂). P. S. buchnerae sp. n., holotype ♂. Scale bars (A to N): 100 µm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2607098/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,406,295,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">Name derivation.</emphasis>
Named in tribute of the Adjamat people (also called the Diolas), partly inhabiting the South of 
<collectingCountry box="[181,270,332,357]" name="Senegal" pageId="4" pageNumber="271">Senegal</collectingCountry>
(Casamance), for their remarkable culture and social structure.
</paragraph>
